{
  "executive_summary": "Event sourcing is an excellent fit for this loan application audit trail use case. The compliance requirements — full field-change history, point-in-time state reconstruction, and immutable audit log — are precisely what event sourcing provides natively. However, event sourcing introduces significant operational complexity. I recommend a hybrid approach: adopt event sourcing for the loan application lifecycle (where audit is mandated) while keeping simpler CRUD patterns for non-regulated supporting domains. This balances regulatory compliance with engineering pragmatism.",

  "architecture": {
    "components": [
      {
        "name": "Loan Application Aggregate",
        "responsibility": "Enforces all business invariants on loan applications. Accepts commands, validates them against current state, and emits domain events. The aggregate is reconstituted by replaying its event stream.",
        "boundaries": "Owns all loan application state transitions: creation, data amendments, status changes, approvals, rejections, withdrawals. Does NOT own user identity or document storage."
      },
      {
        "name": "Event Store",
        "responsibility": "Append-only, immutable persistence of all domain events. Each event is stored with aggregate ID, sequence number, timestamp, event type, payload, and actor metadata. Supports optimistic concurrency via expected sequence numbers.",
        "boundaries": "Write-ahead log for events only. No updates, no deletes. Streams are partitioned by aggregate ID (loan application ID)."
      },
      {
        "name": "Loan Application Read Model (Query Side)",
        "responsibility": "Maintains a materialized current-state projection of each loan application optimized for queries. Built by subscribing to the event stream and applying each event to update a denormalized view. This replaces the existing loan_applications table semantics.",
        "boundaries": "Eventually consistent with the event store. Serves all read queries — application lists, status dashboards, search. Can be rebuilt from scratch by replaying all events."
      },
      {
        "name": "Audit Trail Read Model",
        "responsibility": "Maintains a compliance-oriented projection: a chronological log of every field change with before/after values, actor, timestamp, and correlation to business operations. Supports point-in-time state reconstruction queries.",
        "boundaries": "Read-only, derived from the event stream. Optimized for regulatory queries: 'show me all changes to application X between dates A and B', 'reconstruct application state as of date T'."
      },
      {
        "name": "Command Handler / Application Service",
        "responsibility": "Receives API requests, translates them into domain commands, loads the aggregate from the event store, executes the command, and persists resulting events. Handles idempotency and command validation.",
        "boundaries": "Orchestration layer only — no business logic. Coordinates between the API layer and the domain model."
      },
      {
        "name": "Snapshot Store",
        "responsibility": "Periodically stores materialized aggregate state at a known event sequence number. Used to optimize aggregate loading — instead of replaying all events from the beginning, replay only from the last snapshot.",
        "boundaries": "Performance optimization only. Never the source of truth. Can be deleted and rebuilt without data loss."
      }
    ],
    "interfaces": [
      {
        "from": "API Layer",
        "to": "Command Handler",
        "contract": "HTTP/gRPC commands: SubmitApplication, AmendApplication, ChangeStatus, ApproveApplication, RejectApplication. Each command includes actor identity (user ID, role), idempotency key, and command payload.",
        "coupling_type": "loose — commands are DTOs, no shared domain types"
      },
      {
        "from": "Command Handler",
        "to": "Event Store",
        "contract": "load(aggregateId) → Event[]; append(aggregateId, expectedVersion, Event[]) → void. Optimistic concurrency: append fails if expectedVersion doesn't match current stream length.",
        "coupling_type": "tight — command handler depends on event store interface, but implementation is swappable"
      },
      {
        "from": "Event Store",
        "to": "Read Model Projections",
        "contract": "Subscription/push: events are delivered in order per aggregate stream. Each projection tracks its last processed position. Delivery guarantee: at-least-once with idempotent handlers.",
        "coupling_type": "loose — pub/sub via event stream, projections are independent consumers"
      },
      {
        "from": "Audit Trail Read Model",
        "to": "Compliance API",
        "contract": "Queries: getAuditLog(applicationId, dateRange?), reconstructState(applicationId, asOfTimestamp), getFieldChangeHistory(applicationId, fieldName). Returns immutable audit records.",
        "coupling_type": "loose — read-only query interface"
      },
      {
        "from": "Command Handler",
        "to": "Snapshot Store",
        "contract": "loadSnapshot(aggregateId) → {state, version}?; saveSnapshot(aggregateId, state, version). Used to optimize aggregate hydration for long-lived applications.",
        "coupling_type": "tight — coupled to aggregate serialization format"
      }
    ],
    "data_flow": "1. User action → API receives command with actor identity. 2. Command Handler loads aggregate: fetch latest snapshot (if any) + replay events since snapshot from Event Store. 3. Aggregate validates command against current state, emits zero or more domain events. 4. Command Handler appends events to Event Store with optimistic concurrency check. 5. Event Store publishes events to subscribers. 6. Current-State Projection updates the queryable loan_applications view. 7. Audit Trail Projection appends field-level change records with before/after diffs. 8. Read queries hit projections, never the event store directly. All writes go through the event store — there is a single, immutable, ordered record of everything that happened.",
    "patterns_used": [
      {
        "pattern": "Event Sourcing",
        "rationale": "The compliance requirements ARE event sourcing: immutable log of all changes, point-in-time reconstruction, full field-change history. Event sourcing provides these as first-class capabilities rather than bolted-on audit triggers. In financial services, the event log IS the regulatory record."
      },
      {
        "pattern": "CQRS (Command Query Responsibility Segregation)",
        "rationale": "Event sourcing naturally pairs with CQRS. The write model (event stream) is optimized for consistency and audit; the read models (projections) are optimized for query performance. The audit trail and current-state views have fundamentally different query patterns and update frequencies — separating them avoids compromising either."
      },
      {
        "pattern": "Aggregate Pattern",
        "rationale": "Loan applications have clear consistency boundaries: all status transitions, data amendments, and approval workflows must be serialized per application. The aggregate pattern ensures invariants (e.g., can't approve a rejected application) are enforced in a single transactional scope."
      },
      {
        "pattern": "Snapshot Pattern",
        "rationale": "Loan applications that live for weeks or months may accumulate hundreds of events. Snapshots prevent aggregate load time from growing linearly with application age. Critical for maintaining acceptable latency on write operations."
      },
      {
        "pattern": "Idempotent Command Handling",
        "rationale": "Financial operations must be idempotent. Each command carries an idempotency key; duplicate submissions are detected and return the same result without re-executing. Prevents double-mutations from retries or network issues."
      }
    ]
  },

  "domain_model": {
    "bounded_contexts": [
      {
        "name": "Loan Application Lifecycle",
        "classification": "core",
        "aggregates": [
          "LoanApplication — root aggregate. Entities: Applicant, CoBorrower, LoanTerms, CollateralInfo. Value Objects: ApplicationStatus, Money, Address, SSN (encrypted), CreditScore, AmendmentRecord. Domain Events: ApplicationSubmitted, ApplicantInfoAmended, LoanTermsModified, StatusChangedToUnderReview, ApplicationApproved, ApplicationRejected, ApplicationWithdrawn, DocumentAttached, ConditionAdded, ConditionSatisfied."
        ]
      },
      {
        "name": "Audit & Compliance",
        "classification": "supporting",
        "aggregates": [
          "AuditLog — read model, not a true aggregate. Built from Loan Application events. Stores: FieldChangeRecord (applicationId, fieldPath, oldValue, newValue, changedBy, changedAt, eventId, correlationId). Supports temporal queries and state reconstruction."
        ]
      },
      {
        "name": "Identity & Access Management",
        "classification": "generic",
        "aggregates": [
          "User/Actor — external system. Provides actor identity (userId, role, permissions) included in every command and stamped on every event. Not event-sourced; standard CRUD is fine."
        ]
      },
      {
        "name": "Document Management",
        "classification": "supporting",
        "aggregates": [
          "Document — stores uploaded files (appraisals, income verification, etc.). Referenced by loan application events but stored separately. May or may not benefit from event sourcing depending on complexity."
        ]
      }
    ],
    "context_map": [
      {
        "upstream": "Identity & Access Management",
        "downstream": "Loan Application Lifecycle",
        "relationship": "Conformist — Loan Application accepts the identity model as-is. Every command and event includes actorId and role from IAM. No translation needed."
      },
      {
        "upstream": "Loan Application Lifecycle",
        "downstream": "Audit & Compliance",
        "relationship": "Published Language — Loan Application publishes a well-defined set of domain events. Audit & Compliance subscribes and builds its projections from these events. The event schema is the published contract."
      },
      {
        "upstream": "Loan Application Lifecycle",
        "downstream": "Document Management",
        "relationship": "Customer-Supplier — Loan Application commands may reference documents. Document Management provides storage; Loan Application decides when documents are required."
      }
    ]
  },

  "trade_offs": [
    {
      "decision": "Full event sourcing for loan application lifecycle rather than CRUD + audit triggers",
      "gains": "Immutable audit trail is a natural byproduct, not a bolt-on. Point-in-time reconstruction is trivial (replay events to timestamp). Complete fidelity — you can never lose history. The event log satisfies regulatory requirements by construction, not by hoping triggers fire correctly. Enables new projections without schema migrations.",
      "sacrifices": "Significant increase in operational complexity: event schema evolution, projection rebuild infrastructure, eventual consistency in read models. Steeper learning curve for engineers unfamiliar with event sourcing. Simple queries (e.g., 'get current application state') now require a projection rather than a direct table read.",
      "alternatives_considered": [
        "CRUD + database triggers writing to an audit table — simpler to implement but triggers are fragile, easy to bypass, and reconstructing point-in-time state requires complex temporal joins. Triggers also don't capture intent (why a change was made).",
        "CRUD + Change Data Capture (CDC) via Debezium/similar — captures row-level changes from the WAL. Better than triggers but still loses semantic intent, doesn't capture who/why natively, and couples audit to database internals.",
        "Temporal tables (SQL:2011 / PostgreSQL temporal extensions) — provides system-time versioning with period-of-validity queries. Simpler than event sourcing but captures state snapshots, not semantic events. Cannot reconstruct intent or business meaning of changes. Adequate for simpler compliance needs but insufficient when regulators ask 'why was this change made?'"
      ]
    },
    {
      "decision": "CQRS with separate read projections rather than querying the event store directly",
      "gains": "Read models are optimized for each query pattern: fast current-state lookups, efficient audit trail queries, flexible search. Can add new read models without touching the write side. Read and write can scale independently.",
      "sacrifices": "Eventual consistency between writes and reads — a write may not immediately appear in queries. Additional infrastructure for projection management, rebuild capability, and position tracking. More moving parts to monitor.",
      "alternatives_considered": [
        "Synchronous projections (update projection in same transaction as event append) — eliminates eventual consistency but couples read and write performance and limits scalability.",
        "Query event store directly — simple but terrible query performance for most access patterns. Event stores are optimized for stream reads, not cross-aggregate queries."
      ]
    },
    {
      "decision": "Hybrid approach: event sourcing only for loan application lifecycle, CRUD for supporting/generic contexts",
      "gains": "Concentrates event sourcing complexity where it delivers the most value (regulated domain). Supporting contexts like IAM and document storage remain simple. Reduces total system complexity and team cognitive load.",
      "sacrifices": "Two persistence paradigms to maintain. Integration between event-sourced and CRUD contexts requires careful design at boundaries.",
      "alternatives_considered": [
        "Event source everything — consistent mental model but unnecessary complexity for contexts with no audit requirements.",
        "Event source nothing, use audit triggers everywhere — simpler but doesn't meet the point-in-time reconstruction requirement with high confidence."
      ]
    }
  ],

  "flexibility_points": [
    {
      "area": "Read model projections",
      "evolution_path": "New reporting or compliance requirements can be met by adding new projections that subscribe to the existing event stream. No write-side changes needed. Example: a future requirement for 'average time in each status' can be built as a new projection replayed from the beginning of time."
    },
    {
      "area": "Event schema evolution",
      "evolution_path": "Use event upcasting — each event type has a version, and upcasters transform old event versions to the latest schema on read. This allows the event store to remain immutable while the domain model evolves. Alternatively, use a schema registry for more formal evolution governance."
    },
    {
      "area": "Integration with downstream systems",
      "evolution_path": "The event stream is a natural integration point. Future needs — notifications, analytics, ML models — can subscribe to the event stream without modifying the core domain. This is particularly valuable in financial services where regulatory reporting requirements frequently change."
    },
    {
      "area": "Projection rebuilds",
      "evolution_path": "Any projection can be rebuilt from scratch by replaying all events. This means schema changes in read models are low-risk — destroy and rebuild. Invest in a projection rebuild pipeline early."
    }
  ],

  "rigidity_points": [
    {
      "area": "Event schema (published events)",
      "reason": "Once events are persisted, they are immutable. Renaming an event field or removing an event type is extremely costly — you must support all historical event versions forever (via upcasting) or run a full event store migration. Event schema design must be treated as a public API contract with the same rigor as an external API."
    },
    {
      "area": "Aggregate boundaries",
      "reason": "Splitting or merging aggregates after events are persisted is a major migration. The decision that a LoanApplication is a single aggregate (vs. separate aggregates for ApplicantInfo, LoanTerms, etc.) is hard to reverse. Get this right early."
    },
    {
      "area": "Event store technology choice",
      "reason": "The event store is foundational infrastructure. Switching from, e.g., EventStoreDB to a custom PostgreSQL-based store (or vice versa) after going to production is a significant undertaking. Choose carefully and design the repository interface to abstract the store, but expect the abstraction to leak."
    }
  ],

  "risks": [
    {
      "risk": "Event schema designed poorly upfront — overly granular events, missing context, or coupled to UI structure rather than domain semantics",
      "severity": "critical",
      "mitigation": "Invest heavily in event storming workshops with domain experts before writing code. Events should represent domain-meaningful state transitions (ApplicationApproved), not technical mutations (FieldUpdated). Each event must carry enough context to be independently meaningful. Review event design with the compliance team to ensure events answer the questions regulators will ask."
    },
    {
      "risk": "Team lacks event sourcing experience, leading to misimplementation of core patterns",
      "severity": "high",
      "mitigation": "Start with a proven framework (Axon Framework for JVM, Marten for .NET, or a well-tested PostgreSQL event store library). Invest in team training. Build a spike/proof-of-concept with one aggregate before committing to the full migration. Consider bringing in a consultant with event sourcing production experience for the initial design phase."
    },
    {
      "risk": "Eventual consistency in read models confuses users or creates support issues (e.g., 'I just updated the application but the dashboard shows old data')",
      "severity": "high",
      "mitigation": "Implement read-your-own-writes consistency: after a successful command, return the expected version number and have the client poll the read model until it catches up. Alternatively, use synchronous projection updates for the primary current-state read model (accepting the performance coupling) while keeping audit projections async."
    },
    {
      "risk": "Event store grows unboundedly — millions of events over years of loan processing",
      "severity": "medium",
      "mitigation": "Implement snapshotting for aggregate load performance. For long-term storage, consider archiving closed/completed loan application event streams to cold storage after a configurable retention period (while maintaining compliance-required access). Monitor event store size and query performance as a key operational metric."
    },
    {
      "risk": "Migration from current CRUD system loses or corrupts historical data",
      "severity": "critical",
      "mitigation": "Run dual-write during migration: continue writing to the existing table while also emitting events. Seed the event store with synthetic 'ApplicationImported' events that capture the current state of every existing loan application. Do NOT attempt to reconstruct historical events from the current single-row-per-application data — that data is already lost. Be transparent with compliance that pre-migration history is limited to what the current schema captured."
    },
    {
      "risk": "PII in events creates GDPR/data-privacy tension with immutability — you may be required to delete personal data but events are supposed to be immutable",
      "severity": "high",
      "mitigation": "Use crypto-shredding: encrypt PII fields in events with a per-applicant encryption key. To 'delete' PII, destroy the encryption key — events remain but PII becomes unrecoverable. This satisfies both immutability (for audit) and right-to-erasure (for privacy). Design this from day one; retrofitting crypto-shredding is painful."
    }
  ],

  "implementation_guidance": {
    "recommended_approach": "Phase the implementation over 3 stages. Phase 1 (4-6 weeks): Build the event store infrastructure, implement the LoanApplication aggregate with event sourcing, and create the current-state read model projection. Run in parallel with the existing CRUD system using dual-write. Phase 2 (2-3 weeks): Build the audit trail projection and compliance query API. Validate with the compliance team that the audit trail meets regulatory requirements. Phase 3 (2-3 weeks): Cut over reads from the CRUD table to the new read model. Decommission dual-write. Build projection rebuild tooling and operational monitoring. Throughout: keep the existing loan_applications table as a fallback until confidence is established.",
    "files_to_create_or_modify": [
      "domain/loan_application/aggregate.{ext} — LoanApplication aggregate root with command handlers and event applicators",
      "domain/loan_application/events.{ext} — All domain event types with versioned schemas: ApplicationSubmitted, ApplicantInfoAmended, LoanTermsModified, StatusChanged, ApplicationApproved, ApplicationRejected, ApplicationWithdrawn",
      "domain/loan_application/commands.{ext} — Command types: SubmitApplication, AmendApplicantInfo, ModifyLoanTerms, ChangeStatus, Approve, Reject, Withdraw",
      "infrastructure/event_store/event_store.{ext} — Event store interface: load(streamId), append(streamId, expectedVersion, events)",
      "infrastructure/event_store/pg_event_store.{ext} — PostgreSQL-backed event store implementation with events table (stream_id, version, event_type, payload JSONB, metadata JSONB, created_at, actor_id)",
      "infrastructure/projections/current_state_projection.{ext} — Subscribes to events, maintains the denormalized loan_applications_view table",
      "infrastructure/projections/audit_trail_projection.{ext} — Subscribes to events, maintains field_change_log table with before/after diffs",
      "infrastructure/projections/projection_runner.{ext} — Manages projection lifecycle: position tracking, rebuild capability, error handling",
      "infrastructure/snapshots/snapshot_store.{ext} — Snapshot persistence for aggregate hydration optimization",
      "api/loan_application_command_handler.{ext} — Application service: receives commands, loads aggregate, executes, persists events",
      "api/loan_application_query_handler.{ext} — Query service: reads from projections for current state and audit trail",
      "migration/seed_events.{ext} — Migration script: generates ApplicationImported events for all existing loan applications",
      "infrastructure/event_store/schema.sql — DDL for events, snapshots, and projection position tables"
    ],
    "patterns_to_follow": "Use a consistent command → aggregate → events → projection pipeline. Every command handler follows the same pattern: (1) load aggregate from event store, (2) call aggregate method which validates and returns events, (3) append events to store, (4) return success. Aggregates should be pure — no I/O, no side effects, just state + decision logic. Events are past-tense named facts (ApplicationSubmitted, not SubmitApplication). Projections are idempotent event handlers that track their position in the stream. Use correlation IDs to trace a command through to its resulting events and projection updates.",
    "pitfalls_to_avoid": [
      "Do NOT create a generic 'FieldChanged' event — this destroys domain semantics and makes the audit trail meaningless to regulators. Events must represent business-meaningful transitions.",
      "Do NOT store derived/computed data in events — events should capture facts, projections should compute views.",
      "Do NOT allow direct database writes that bypass the event store — every mutation must go through the aggregate and produce events, or the audit trail has gaps.",
      "Do NOT skip event versioning from day one — even v1 events should have explicit version numbers to enable future upcasting.",
      "Do NOT build a synchronous event bus where projection failure blocks the write — use an outbox pattern or transactional subscription for reliability without coupling.",
      "Do NOT ignore the existing data migration — every current loan application needs a synthetic import event or it will be invisible to the new system.",
      "Do NOT store PII in plaintext in events without a crypto-shredding strategy — you will regret this when the first GDPR deletion request arrives."
    ]
  },

  "escalations": [],

  "confidence": {
    "level": 88,
    "high_confidence_areas": [
      "Event sourcing is the right pattern for this specific use case — the compliance requirements map almost 1:1 to event sourcing capabilities",
      "CQRS is necessary alongside event sourcing for acceptable query performance",
      "The hybrid approach (event sourcing for loan lifecycle, CRUD for supporting contexts) is the pragmatic choice",
      "Crypto-shredding is the correct approach for PII + immutability tension",
      "The aggregate boundary (one LoanApplication aggregate) is correct for the described scope"
    ],
    "low_confidence_areas": [
      "Optimal event store technology choice — depends on existing tech stack, team expertise, and infrastructure constraints which are not specified",
      "Exact event granularity — requires event storming with domain experts; the events I listed are a reasonable starting point but will evolve",
      "Whether synchronous or asynchronous projection updates are right for the current-state read model — depends on latency tolerance and usage patterns"
    ],
    "assumptions": [
      "The engineering team has or can acquire sufficient event sourcing expertise to implement and operate this system",
      "The existing loan_applications table data does not include historical changes that need to be preserved (since it's update-in-place, that history is already lost)",
      "The platform uses a relational database (PostgreSQL assumed) that can serve as both event store and read model store",
      "Loan application volume is moderate (thousands to low millions) — not billions of events requiring specialized event store infrastructure",
      "The compliance team's requirement for point-in-time reconstruction means they need to reconstruct the full application state, not just see a list of changes"
    ]
  }
}
